Steps of the Analysis

  1. Data Loading & Inspection

    • The dataset was imported and displayed, containing key features such as gender, age, hypertension, heart_disease, avg_glucose_level, bmi, and smoking_status.
    • The target variable was stroke, where 1 indicates a person had a stroke and 0 indicates they did not.

  2. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

    • You checked data balance using df.stroke.value_counts().
    • It was found that only 5% of the data represented stroke cases (248 vs 4733 non-stroke cases), showing strong class imbalance.
    • Insights were likely visualized with bar plots or histograms to understand the distribution of age, glucose level, and BMI across stroke and non-stroke groups.

  3. Data Preprocessing

    • Missing values were handled (especially for BMI).
    • Categorical features such as gender, work_type, and smoking_status were encoded numerically using OrdinalEncoder or OneHotEncoder.
    • The dataset was shuffled and normalized with MinMaxScaler to scale all feature values between 0 and 1 for better model performance.

  4. Train-Test Split

    • The dataset was split into training and testing sets to evaluate model generalization.

  5. Model Training

    • A Logistic Regression model was applied as the first baseline classifier.
    • Initial results showed 96% accuracy, but the confusion matrix revealed that the model predicted almost all samples as non-stroke, meaning it overfitted to the majority class.

  6. Handling Class Imbalance

    • To fix overfitting, the SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) method was applied to balance the dataset.
    • SMOTE generated synthetic samples for the minority class (stroke cases), helping the model learn both classes equally.

  7. Re-Training & Evaluation

    • After SMOTE, the Logistic Regression model was re-trained and evaluated again.
    • The metrics such as precision, recall, and F1-score for the stroke class improved significantly, showing better predictive power on minority cases.
    • Accuracy alone was no longer the focus the model aimed for balanced performance across both classes.

Conclusion

The Brain Stroke Classification project demonstrates a complete data science pipeline from data cleaning and exploration to model evaluation and class balancing. Initially, the model achieved high accuracy but failed to identify stroke cases due to class imbalance. By applying SMOTE, you improved the models sensitivity to minority cases, resulting in a fairer and more reliable classifier.

In summary: Built a medical classification model capable of predicting stroke risk, showcasing your skills in data preprocessing, feature encoding, normalization, and class balancing all critical components in building trustworthy health-related machine learning models.

In[28]:
# Create a function to fit and score models
def fit_and_score(models, X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val):
    # Set random seed
    np.random.seed(42)
    # Make a dictionary to keep model scores
    model_scores = {}
    # Loop through models
    for name, model in models.items():
        # Fit the model to the data
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        # Evaluate the model and append its score to model_scores
        model_scores[name] = model.score(X_val, y_val)
    return model_scores

Since the number of people without stroke is less than people with stroke, our model is overfiting. There is a 98% of every guess be right. Let apply the Smote and see how our model will perform with balanced data

Smote

In[40]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

print(f"Difference between people with Stroke and without Stroke {np.bincount(y)}. 19x more information.\n\n") 

smt = SMOTE()
X_resampled, y_resampled = smt.fit_resample(X,y)
print(f"Smote creates new lines with similar data to balance the variable with less values. After apply Smote {np.bincount(y_resampled)} the numbers are equal.\n")

Difference between people with Stroke and without Stroke [4733  248]. 19x more information.


Smote creates new lines with similar data to balance the variable with less values. After apply Smote [4733 4733] the numbers are equal.

#shuffle dataset again
from sklearn.utils import shuffle
